<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicName authority="Mayr, 1881" authorityName="Mayr" authorityYear="1881" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Rhoophilus Mayr, 1881</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Rhoophilus</taxonomicName>
is morphologically similar to the Holarctic inquiline genera 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Synergus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Synergus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Synergus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Dalla Torre &amp; Kieffer, 1910" authorityName="Dalla Torre &amp; Kieffer" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Saphonecrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Saphonecrus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Saphonecrus</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Synophrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Synophrus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Synophrus</taxonomicName>
, all of which typically attack oak cynipid galls. The transverse ridges of the mesoscutum, and a mesopleuron sculptured with longitudinal ridges in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Rhoophilus</taxonomicName>
closely resemble characters in several species of the 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Curculionidae" genus="Synergus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Synergus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Synergus</taxonomicName>
/ 
<taxonomicName authority="Dalla Torre &amp; Kieffer, 1910" authorityName="Dalla Torre &amp; Kieffer" authorityYear="1910" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Saphonecrus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Saphonecrus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Saphonecrus</taxonomicName>
complex. A sister group relationship between 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Rhoophilus</taxonomicName>
and these three oak inquiline genera was hypothesized by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ronquist, F" journalOrPublisher="Evolution" pageId="159" pageNumber="160" pagination="241 - 266" title="Evolution of parasitism among closely related species: Phylogenetic relationships and the origin of inquilinism in gall wasps (Hymenoptera, Cynipidae)." url="10.2307/2410091" volume="48" year="1994">Ronquist (1994)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Liljeblad, J" journalOrPublisher="Systematic Entomology" pageId="154" pageNumber="155" pagination="229 - 252" title="A phylogenetic analysis of higher-level gall wasp relationships (Hymenoptera: Cynipidae)." url="10.1046/j.1365-3113.1998.00053.x" volume="23" year="1998">Liljeblad and Ronquist (1998)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="14" pageNumber="15" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<pageBreakToken pageId="14" pageNumber="15" start="start">Diagnosis</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="15">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Rhoophilus</taxonomicName>
has a closed marginal cell, a character shared with 
<taxonomicName authority="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika, 2011" authorityName="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Qwaqwaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Qwaqwaia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Qwaqwaia</taxonomicName>
. The areolet is triangular as in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Phanacis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phanacis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phanacis</taxonomicName>
, but larger and more distinct, whereas it is elongate rhomboidal in 
<taxonomicName authority="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika, 2011" authorityName="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Qwaqwaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Qwaqwaia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Qwaqwaia</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Rhoophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Rhoophilus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Rhoophilus</taxonomicName>
lacks an occipital carina as in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Phanacis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phanacis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phanacis</taxonomicName>
(present in 
<taxonomicName authority="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika, 2011" authorityName="Liljeblad, Nieves-Aldrey &amp; Melika" authorityYear="2011" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Qwaqwaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Qwaqwaia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Qwaqwaia</taxonomicName>
), but has tergites 2 and 3 fused, whereas these are free in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Phanacis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Phanacis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="15" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Phanacis</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
